Queens Boulevard, south side, west from near 55th Road, shoowLng old frame houses and the First Presbyterian Church of Newtown. The first house (left) was owned by P. Rapelye. the second by G. Rapelye, and the one nearest the church by Burns, in 1873. The
houses are being demolished.
View 3 shows a closer view of the Burns house: view 4 is from 55th Road and shows the houses gone. The two hor es in view 4
do not appear in the other views.
View 1: December 27, 1922
Views 2,3: December 29, 1922

Queens Boulevard, north side, west from 55th Rd. to Broadway in 4 views showing the old Presbyterian Church of Newtown. See other views. View No. S shows an eastward view from Broadway. The original church was erected in 1671 and stood on the south side of the road opposite this durch. It was occupied by Episcopalians from 1703-1708. The Chapel of this church was removed and used as a Sabbath School.
1922
Views 1 and 2.
View 3 Jan 1923.
View 4: Oct. 18, 1928.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

Queens Boulevard, west from 55th Road, showing on both sides of the Boulevard, the old (steepled) and the new First Presbyterian Church of Newtown. The church at the left once was steepled but it was removed when the church was moved back from its former site.
